    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "I kind of disagree with major versions here, given the already prevailing use of \"Ethereum 2.0\". IMO it would be a bit more appropriate for spec versions to be, say, 1.x.y, pre-merge and then after the merge start using 2.x.y. This _seems_ to be what [eth2.0-specs](https://github.com/ethereum/eth2.0-specs/releases/) is using. \r\n\r\nAs for choosing the next hard fork, the process is listed [here](https://github.com/ethereum/eth1.0-specs/tree/master/network-upgrades). If you assume a certain upgrade is represented by the middle digit (e.g. 1.1.y), then perhaps we can increment `y` each time a change is made to either include EIPs in a devnet, or to move them to the network upgrade spec, with at most one release every 2 weeks aside from emergencies. ",
